<section xml:id="section-variables-and-evaluating-expressions">
    <title>Variables and Evaluating Expressions</title>
    <objectives>
        <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <xref ref="ccog-evaluate-algebraic-expressions" text="local">MTH 60 CCOG</xref>
            </li>
            <li>
                <xref ref="ccog-distinguish-between-evaluating-simplifying-solving" text="local">MTH 60 CCOG</xref>
            </li>
            <li>
                <xref ref="ccog-properly-define-variables" text="local">MTH 60 CCOG</xref>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Variables and expressions are the basic building blocks for writing algebra.
            In this section, we become familar with how to use them.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="video-variables-and-evaluating-expressions">
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtubeplaylist="PLmuZCPhWPt-cOp0ZMJHO6zy0bhdu2gKjQ"/>
        </figure>
    </introduction>
    <subsection>
        <title>Introduction to Variables</title>
        <p>
            When we want to represent an unknown quantity or a quantity that can change its value,
            we use a <term>variable</term>.
                    <idx><h>variable</h></idx>
            For example,
            if you'd like to discuss the gas mileage of different cars,
            you could use the symbol <q><m>g</m></q> as a variable
            to represent a car's gas mileage.
            The gas mileage <m>g</m> might be
            <quantity>
                <mag>25</mag><unit base="milepergallon"/>
            </quantity>,
            for one car,
            <quantity>
                <mag>30</mag><unit base="milepergallon"/>
            </quantity>,
            for some other car, and many other values for other cars.
            (<q><quantity>
                <unit base="milepergallon"/>
            </quantity></q>
            stands for <q>miles per gallon</q>.)
            If we agree to use
            <quantity>
                <unit base="milepergallon"/>
            </quantity>
            for the units of measure,
            <m>g</m> might be a placeholder for <m>25</m>,
            <m>30</m>, or some other number.
            Since we are using a variable and not a specific number,
            we can discuss gas mileage for Honda Civics, Ford Explorers,
            and all other makes and models at the same time,
            even though these makes and models have different gas mileages.
        </p>
        <p>
            When variables stand for actual physical quantities,
            it's good to use letters that clearly represent those quantities.
            For example,
            it's wise to use <m>g</m> to represent <em>g</em>as mileage.
            This helps the people who might read your work to understand it better.
        </p>
        <p>
            It is also important to clearly identify what unit of measurement goes along with each variable you use.
            For example, suppose you are working with <m>g=25</m>.
            A car whose gas mileage is
            <quantity>
                <mag>25</mag><unit base="milepergallon"/>
            </quantity>
            is very different from a car whose gas mileage is
            <quantity>
                <mag>25</mag><unit base="kilometerpergallon"/>
            </quantity>
            (kilometers per gallon).
            So it would be important to tell readers that <m>g</m> represents gas mileage
            <em>in miles per gallon</em>.
        </p>
        <exercise>
            <title>Naming Variables</title>
            <webwork>
                <pg-code>
                    Context()-&gt;variables-&gt;are();
                    for my $i (1..26) {
                            Context()-&gt;variables-&gt;add($ALPHABET[$i-1]=&gt;'Real');
                            Context()-&gt;variables-&gt;add(lc($ALPHABET[$i-1])=&gt;'Real');
                            };
                    Context()-&gt;strings-&gt;add('years'=&gt;{});
                    Context()-&gt;strings-&gt;add(
                        'year'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'years'},
                        'yrs'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'years'},
                        'yr'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'years'},
                        'yrs.'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'years'},
                        'yr.'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'years'},
                        'y.'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'years'}
                    );
                    Context()-&gt;strings-&gt;add('hours'=&gt;{});
                    Context()-&gt;strings-&gt;add(
                        'hour'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'hours'},
                        'hrs'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'hours'},
                        'hr'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'hours'},
                        'h'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'hours'},
                        'hrs.'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'hours'},
                        'hr.'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'hours'},
                        'h.'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'hours'}
                    );
                    Context()-&gt;strings-&gt;add('miles'=&gt;{});
                    Context()-&gt;strings-&gt;add(
                        'mile'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'miles'},
                        'mis'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'miles'},
                        'mi'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'miles'},
                        'm'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'miles'},
                        'mis.'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'hours'},
                        'mi.'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'miles'},
                        'm.'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'miles'}
                    );
                    Context()-&gt;strings-&gt;add('square feet'=&gt;{});
                    Context()-&gt;strings-&gt;add(
                        'ft^2'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'square feet'},
                        'feet squared'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'square feet'},
                        'feet square'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'square feet'},
                        'sq ft'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'square feet'},
                        'sqft'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'square feet'},
                        'sq. ft.'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'square feet'},
                        'ft.^2'=&gt;{alias=&gt;'square feet'}
                    );
                    $a=OneOf('a','A','x','y','z');
                    $t=OneOf('t','T','x','y','z');
                </pg-code>
                <introduction>
                    <p>
                        Identify a variable you might use to represent each quantity.
                        Then identify what units would be most appropriate.
                    </p>
                </introduction>
                <task>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <var name="$a" width="2"/> be the age of a student,
                            measured in <var name="'years'" width="10"/>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            The unknown quantity is age, which we generally measure in years.
                            So we could say <q>Let <m>a</m> be the age of a student, measured in years.</q>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </task>
                <task>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <var name="$t" width="2"/> be the amount of time passed since a driver left Portland, Oregon,
                            bound for Boise, Idaho, measured in <var name="'hours'" width="10"/>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            The amount of time passed is the unknown quantity.
                            Since this is a drive from Portland to Boise,
                            it would make sense to measure this in hours.
                            So we could say
                            <q>Let <m>t</m> be the amount of time passed since a driver left Portland, Oregon,
                            bound for Boise, Idaho, measured in hours.</q>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </task>
                <task>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <var name="$a" width="2"/> be the area of a two-bedroom apartment,
                            measured in <var name="'square feet'" width="10"/>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            The unknown quantity is area.
                            Apartment area is usually measured in square feet.
                            So we'll say:
                            <q>Let <m>A</m> be the area of a two-bedroom apartment,
                            measured in <m>\text{ft}^2</m>.</q>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </task>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <p>
            Unless an algebra problem specifies which letter(s) to use,
            <em>we may choose</em> which letter(s) to use for our variable(s).
            Without any context to a problem, <m>x</m>,
            <m>y</m>,
            and <m>z</m> are the most common letters used as variables.
            You may see these variables
            (especially <m>x</m>)
            a lot.
        </p>
        <p>
            Also note that the units we use are often suggested by the information given in an algebra problem.
            For example,
            if we're told that a car has used so many <em>gallons</em> of gas after traveling so many <em>miles</em>,
            then this suggests we should measure gas mileage in
            <quantity>
                <unit base="milepergallon"/>
            </quantity>.
        </p>
    </subsection>
    <subsection>
        <title>Algebraic Expressions</title>
        <p>
            Any combination of variables and numbers using arithmetic operations
            is an <term>algebraic expression</term>.
                    <idx><h>expression</h><h>algebraic</h></idx>
                    <idx><h>algebraic expression</h></idx>
            The following are examples of algebraic expressions:
            <me>
                x+1\qquad 2\ell+2w\qquad\frac{\sqrt{x}}{y+1}\qquad nRT
            </me>
            Note that this definition of <q>algebraic expression</q> does <em>not</em>
            include anything with an equals sign (<m>=</m>) in it.
        </p>
        <example xml:id="example-evaluate-temperature">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The expression:
                    <me>
                        \frac{5}{9}(F - 32)
                    </me>
                    converts a temperature in degrees Fahrenheit to degrees Celsius.
                    To do this, we need a Fahrenheit temperature, <m>F</m>.
                    Then we can <term>evaluate</term>
                            <idx><h>evaluate</h></idx>
                    the expression.
                    This means replacing its variable(s) with specific numbers and finding the result as a single,
                    simplified number.
                </p>
                <p oldpermid="QjJ">
                    Let's convert the temperature
                    <quantity>
                        <mag>89</mag><unit base="fahrenheit"/>
                    </quantity>
                    to the Celsius scale by evaluating the expression.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\frac{5}{9}(F - 32) \amp= \frac{5}{9}(\substitute{89} - 32)\amp\amp\text{Review order of operations in }<xref ref="section-order-of-operations"/>\text{.}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp= \frac{5}{9}(57)\amp\amp\text{Review fraction multiplication in }<xref ref="section-fractions-and-fraction-arithmetic"/>\text{.}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp= \frac{285}{9}\approx 31.67</mrow>
                    </md>
                    This shows us that
                    <quantity>
                        <mag>89</mag><unit base="fahrenheit"/>
                    </quantity>
                    is approximately the same temperature as
                    <quantity>
                        <mag>31.67</mag><unit base="celsius"/>
                    </quantity>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </example>
        <warning>
            <title>Correct Vocabulary</title>
            <p>
                The steps in <xref ref="example-evaluate-temperature">Example</xref>
                are not considered <q>solving</q> anything. <q>Solving</q>
                is a word you might want to use,
                because in everyday English you are <q>finding an answer.</q>
                In algebra, there is a special meaning for <q>solving</q> something,
                and that will come soon in <xref ref="section-solving-one-step-equations">Section</xref>.
                When we substitute values in for variables and then compute the result,
                we are <q>evaluating an expression,</q> not solving anything.
            </p>
        </warning>
        <exercise>
            <title>Convert Temperature</title>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    Try evaluating the temperature expression for yourself.
                </p>
            </introduction>
            <webwork>
                <pg-code>
                    Context("Numeric");
                    $celsius[0] = NumberWithUnits(10,'degC');
                    $celsius[1] = NumberWithUnits(-260/9,'degC');
                </pg-code>
                <task>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            If a temperature is <m>50{^\circ}\mathrm{F}</m>, what is that temperature measured in Celsius?
                        </p>
                        <instruction>
                            You may use <c>degC</c> for <m>^{\circ}\mathrm{C}</m>.
                        </instruction>
                        <p>
                            <var name="$celsius[0]" width="20"/>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <m>\begin{aligned}[t]
                            \frac{5}{9}(F - 32)\amp=\frac{5}{9}(\substitute{50} - 32)\\
                            \amp=\frac{5}{9}(18)\\
                            \amp=\frac{5}{1}(2)\\
                            \amp=10
                            \end{aligned}
                            </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            So <m>50{^\circ}\mathrm{F}</m> is equavalent to <m>10{^\circ}\mathrm{C}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </task>
                <task>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            If a temperature is <m>-20{^\circ}\mathrm{F}</m>, what is that temperature measured in Celsius?
                        </p>
                        <instruction>
                            You may use <c>degC</c> for <m>^{\circ}\mathrm{C}</m>.
                        </instruction>
                        <p>
                            <var name="$celsius[1]" width="20"/>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <m>\begin{aligned}[t]
                            \frac{5}{9}(F - 32)\amp=\frac{5}{9}(\substitute{-20} - 32)\\
                            \amp=\frac{5}{9}(-52)\\
                            \amp=-\frac{260}{9}\\
                            \amp\approx-28.89
                            \end{aligned}
                            </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            So <m>-20{^\circ}\mathrm{F}</m> is equavalent to about <m>-28.89{^\circ}\mathrm{C}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </task>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <example>
            <title>Allowing Variables to Vary</title>
            <p>With the help of technology, it is possible to quickly evaluate expressions as variables vary. In the GeoGebra applet in <xref ref="figure-geogebra-fahrenheit">Figure</xref>, you may slide the value of <m>F</m> and see how a computer can quickly calculate the correspoding Celsius temperature.</p>
            <figure xml:id="figure-geogebra-fahrenheit">
                <caption>Allowing Variables to Vary</caption>
                <interactive xml:id="geogebra-fahrenheit" platform="geogebra" aspect="3:2">
                    <slate surface="geogebra" aspect="3:2">
                        setPerspective("G");
                        setCoordSystem(-1,1,-1,1);
                        setAxesVisible(false, false);
                        setGridVisible(false);
                        evalCommand("F = Slider(20,120,1)");
                        evalCommand("F = 20");
                        evalCommand("s = F-32");
                        evalCommand("g = GCD(s,9)");
                        evalCommand("num = s/g");
                        evalCommand("den = 9/g");
                        evalCommand("newnum = 5*num");
                        evalCommand("C = newnum/den");
                        evalCommand('reduced=If(g==1,"","&amp;=\\frac{5}{"+den+"}\\cdot\\frac{"+num+"}{1}\\\\")');
                        setVisible("reduced",false);
                        evalCommand('final=If(Mod(newnum,den)==0,"&amp;="+C,"&amp;\\approx"+C)');
                        setVisible("final",false);
                        setRounding("3");
                        evalCommand('simple=If(s==0 || s==1 || s==-1,"",Text("&amp;=\\frac{5}{9}\\cdot\\frac{"+s+"}{1}\\\\"+reduced+"&amp;=\\frac{"+newnum+"}{"+den+"}\\\\"))');
                        setVisible("simple",false);
                        evalCommand('evaluation=Text("\\begin{aligned}\\frac{5}{9}(F-32)&amp;=\\frac{5}{9}("+F+"-32)\\\\&amp;=\\frac{5}{9}("+s+")\\\\"+simple+final+"\\end{aligned}",(-0.9,0.6),true,true)');
                        evalCommand('about=If(Mod(newnum,den)==0,"","about ")');
                        setVisible("about",false);
                        evalCommand('conclusion=Text("\\text{A Fahrenheit temperature of }"+F+"^{\\circ}\\mathrm{F}\\\\\\text{corresponds to a Celsius}\\\\\\text{temperature of }{"+C+"}^{\\circ}\\mathrm{C}\\text{.}",(0,0.5),true,true)');
                        enableShiftDragZoom(false);
                    </slate>
                </interactive>
            </figure>
        </example>
        <example>
            <title>Stair Rise and Run</title>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    When building a staircase, you want the rise and run to be constant form one step to the next.
                </p>
                <image decorative="yes" width="47%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[x=0.7mm,y=0.7mm]
                            \foreach \x in {0,...,3}
                                \draw [fill=firstcolor!20] (10*\x, 12*\x) --++ (-30,15) --++ (0,7) --++ (30,-15);
                            \draw (0,0) --++ (0,7) --++ (10,5) --++ (0,7) --++ (10,5) --++ (0,7) --++ (10,5) --++ (0,7) --++ (10,5);
                            \draw (-30,15) --++ (0,7) --++ (10,5) node[pos=0.5, sloped, above] {run} --++ (0,7) --++ (10,5) --++ (0,7) --++ (10,5) --++ (0,7) --++ (10,5);
                            \draw (0,0) -- (40,20) --++ (0,28) --++ (-30,15);
                            \node[left] at (-30,18.5) {rise};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                <p>
                    A conventional rule among contractors is that the run, in inches, is given by <m>17.5-h</m>,
                    where <m>h</m> is the rise in inches.
                </p>
            </introduction>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Determine the run for each step of a staircase where the rise is <quantity><mag>7</mag><unit base="inch"/></quantity>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        We evaluate
                        <md>
                            <mrow>17.5-h\amp=17.5-\substitute{7}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=10.5</mrow>
                        </md>.
                        So the run is <quantity><mag>10.5</mag><unit base="inch"/></quantity>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A staircase needs to span a total height of <quantity><mag>108</mag><unit base="inch"/></quantity>.
                        What is a reasonable number of steps for it to have? What will that mean for the rise of each step?
                        What will the run be for each step?
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        There is more than one good answer, but if there are <m>12</m> steps
                        then the height of each step will be <m>\frac{108}{12}</m> inches, or <quantity><mag>9</mag><unit base="inch"/></quantity>.
                        And that mean the run of each step is found by evaluating
                        <md>
                            <mrow>17.5-h\amp=17.5-\substitute{9}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=8.5</mrow>
                        </md>.
                        So each step would have a run of <quantity><mag>8.5</mag><unit base="inch"/></quantity>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </example>
        <exercise>
            <title>Stair Rise and Run</title>
            <webwork>
                <pg-code>
                    $run = NumberWithUnits('9.75 in');
                </pg-code>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        The expression <m>17.5-h</m> gives the run of a stairstep when the rise is <m>h</m> inches.
                        Determine the run for each step of a staircase where the rise is <quantity><mag>7.75</mag><unit base="inch"/></quantity>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <var name="$run" width="10"/>
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        We evaluate
                        <md>
                            <mrow>17.5-h\amp=17.5-\substitute{7.75}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=9.75</mrow>
                        </md>.
                        So the run is <quantity><mag>9.75</mag><unit base="inch"/></quantity>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <title>Rising Rents</title>
            <webwork>
                <pg-code>
                    $r=32.35;
                    $b=620;
                    Context("Currency");
                    Context("Currency")-&gt;currency-&gt;addSymbol("dollars","dollar");
                    Context()-&gt;flags-&gt;set(tolerance=&gt;1);
                    Context()-&gt;flags-&gt;set(trimTrailingZeros=&gt;1);
                    @rent=map{Currency($b+$r*$_)}(10,21,25);
                    for my $i (0,1,2) {$rentev[$i]=$rent[$i]-&gt;cmp(cmp_class =&gt;"an amount of money");};
                </pg-code>
                <introduction>
                    <p>
                        In the state of Oregon starting from the year 2000,
                        the median rent among all rental living units has closely followed the expression <m>620+32.35x</m>,
                        where <m>x</m> is the number of years since the year 2000.
                    </p>
                </introduction>
                <task>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            According to this model,
                            what was the median rent for a living unit in Oregon in 2010?
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <var name="$rent[0]" evaluator="$rentev[0]" width="10"/>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            This model uses <m>x</m> as the number of years since 2000.
                            So for the year 2010, <m>x</m> is <m>10</m>:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>620+32.35x \amp=620+32.35(\substitute{10})</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp = 943.50</mrow>
                            </md>
                            According to this model,
                            the average monthly rent for a living unit in Oregon in 2010 was <m>\$943.50</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </task>
                <task>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            According to this model,
                            what was the median rent for a living unit in Oregon in 2021?
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <var name="$rent[1]" evaluator="$rentev[1]" width="10"/>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            This model uses <m>x</m> as the number of years since 2000.
                            So for the year 2021, <m>x</m> is <m>21</m>:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>620+32.35x \amp=620+32.35(\substitute{21})</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp = 1299.35</mrow>
                            </md>
                            According to this model,
                            the average monthly rent for a living unit in Oregon in 2021 was <m>\$1299.35</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </task>
                <task>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            According to this model,
                            what will be the median rent for a living unit in Oregon in 2025?
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <var name="$rent[2]" evaluator="$rentev[2]" width="10"/>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            This model uses <m>x</m> as the number of years since 2000.
                            So for the year 2025, <m>x</m> is <m>25</m>:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>620+32.35x \amp=620+32.35(\substitute{25})</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp = 1428.75</mrow>
                            </md>
                            According to this model,
                            the average monthly rent for a living unit in Oregon in 2025 will be <m>\$1428.75</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </task>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>
    </subsection>
    <subsection>
        <title>Evaluating Expressions with Exponents, Absolute Value, and Radicals</title>
        <p>
            Algebraic expressions will often have exponents,
            absolute value bars, and radicals.
            This does not change the basic approach to evaluating them.
        </p>
        <example>
            <title>Tsunami Speed</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The speed of a tsunami
                    (in meters per second)
                    can be modeled by <m>\sqrt{9.8d}</m>,
                    where <m>d</m> is the depth of the tsunami
                    (in meters).
                    Determine the speed of a tsunami that has a depth of
                    <quantity>
                        <mag>30</mag><unit base="meter"/>
                    </quantity>
                    to four significant digits.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Using <m>d=30</m>, we find:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{9.8d} \amp= \sqrt{9.8(\substitute{30})}\amp\amp\text{Review order of operations in }<xref ref="section-order-of-operations"/>\text{.}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{294}\amp\amp\text{Review square root in }<xref ref="section-absolute-value-and-square-root"/>\text{.}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp\approx \overbrace{17.14}^{\text{four}}6428\ldots</mrow>
                    </md>
                    The speed of tsunami with a depth of
                    <quantity>
                        <mag>30</mag><unit base="meter"/>
                    </quantity>
                    is about
                    <quantity>
                        <mag>17.15</mag><unit base="meter"/><per base="second"/>
                    </quantity>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <p>
            Up to now, we have been evaluating expressions,
            but we can evaluate formulas in the same way.
            A <term>formula</term>
                    <idx><h>formula</h></idx>
            usually has a single variable that represents the result of an expression,
            and one or more variables that you can evaluate with.
            For example,
            the expression for a person's maximum heart rate in beats per minute,
            <m>220-a</m>, can be written as the formula, <m>H=220-a</m>.
            When we substitute a value for <m>a</m> we are <q>evaluating</q> the formula.
        </p>
